---
import DocsLayout from '@/layouts/DocsLayout.astro'
---
<DocsLayout
  title="Local Development"
  description="Run your app locally with Docker Compose, Caddy reverse proxy, and mkcert SSL certificates — matching production as closely as possible."
  section="dev"
>
  <p>
    <code>shuttle dev</code> spins up a local development environment that mirrors your production
    setup. It reads your <code>shuttle.yml</code>, generates a <code>docker-compose.dev.yml</code>
    and a <code>Caddyfile.dev</code>, optionally provisions mkcert SSL certificates, and runs
    everything with <code>docker compose up</code>.
  </p>

  <h2>Quick start</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle dev          # start (default subcommand is "up")
shuttle dev up       # same as above
shuttle dev down     # stop all containers
shuttle dev restart  # down + up
shuttle dev logs     # stream logs from all containers
shuttle dev status   # show running containers and ports
</code></pre>

  <h2>What shuttle dev up does</h2>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>SSL setup</strong> — checks for existing certs at <code>.shuttle/certs/</code>. If mkcert is installed, generates trusted certificates for your domain(s). Falls back to plain HTTP if mkcert is missing.</li>
    <li><strong>Generate Caddyfile.dev</strong> — writes <code>.shuttle/Caddyfile.dev</code> with a reverse proxy entry pointing to your app container port. If certs exist, configures TLS with <code>tls cert.pem key.pem</code>.</li>
    <li><strong>Generate docker-compose.dev.yml</strong> — writes a compose file in the project root with all services (app, accessories from <code>shuttle.yml</code>) and a Caddy service (when SSL is available).</li>
    <li><strong>docker compose up -d --build</strong> — starts all containers in detached mode, building from your Dockerfile.</li>
    <li><strong>Print URLs</strong> — shows <code>https://&lt;your-domain&gt;</code> and <code>https://localhost</code>. Mailpit UI is shown at <code>http://localhost:8025</code> if configured.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2>Dev configuration block</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-yaml">dev:
  ssl: true                  # enable mkcert SSL (default: true)
  domain: my-app.test        # override domain for local dev (defaults to top-level domain)
  ports:
    http: 80                 # host port for HTTP (default: 80)
    https: 443               # host port for HTTPS (default: 443)
</code></pre>

  <h2>Generated files</h2>
  <p>
    Shuttle generates two files that you can inspect or customize:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><code>.shuttle/Caddyfile.dev</code> — Caddy configuration for local dev</li>
    <li><code>docker-compose.dev.yml</code> — compose file in project root</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    These files are regenerated on every <code>shuttle dev up</code> call. Add them to
    <code>.gitignore</code> unless you want to commit the generated config:
  </p>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">docker-compose.dev.yml
.shuttle/Caddyfile.dev
.shuttle/certs/
</code></pre>

  <h2>Accessories in dev</h2>
  <p>
    All <code>accessories:</code> defined in <code>shuttle.yml</code> are included in the dev
    compose file. Named volumes from remote paths (<code>/data/...</code>) are converted to
    local Docker volumes so data persists across restarts.
  </p>
  <p>
    Example: if your production config has a Postgres accessory, <code>shuttle dev up</code>
    starts Postgres locally as well — same image, same environment variables.
  </p>

  <h2>Logs</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle dev logs          # stream all logs (follows by default)
shuttle dev logs --no-follow   # print logs and exit
</code></pre>

  <h2>Status</h2>
  <pre><code class="language-bash">shuttle dev status
# NAME                IMAGE               COMMAND                  STATUS
# myapp-web-1         myapp-web           "node server.js"         Up 3 minutes
# myapp-caddy-1       caddy:2-alpine      "caddy run --config…"    Up 3 minutes
# myapp-postgres-1    postgres:16         "docker-entrypoint.s…"   Up 3 minutes
</code></pre>
</DocsLayout>
